<br>
I am deeply, deeply offended.  Are you trying to say that because I choose not to use physical violence against a fellow human being, that I am a coward?  If I am a coward, does that make the people committing these horrendous acts of violence brave?  Who is really brave, the unarmed person facing the armed person, or the armed person facing the unarmed?  I'm not a pacifist because I am a coward.  I despise cowardice -- almost as much as I despise violence.  Is that clear?<br>
I pray that I am never in a situation where someone attacks my students.  But I will tell you right now that I would NOT BE RUNNING.  The first thing I would do is try to talk the armed attacker into putting the weapon away.  If I could not do this, I would request that he let the children go and take me as a hostage.  If he would not let the children go, I would request that he not harm them, but harm me instead.  And if he refused to do that, I'd try to block the bullet or knife with my own body.<br>
Children are precious.  That's why I'm a teacher.  I would rather die myself than let one of them be harmed.<br>
