<br>
  In the US you carry a gun, and you justify it by saying &quot;I need it to protect myself against criminals&quot;<br>
<br>
  In NZ we don't carry guns, and we justify it by saying &quot;Our police force will protect us against criminals&quot;<br>
<br>
  Neither method is perfect... but we have a FAR lower incidence of violent crime with guns per capita here in NZ than you do in the US.  <br>
<br>
  Something to think about, yes?<br>
<br>
Cyrus<br>
<br>
  (Yeah, there are other factors as well.  It's not as cut and dried as the data would suggest... NZ doesn't have the same pressures that the US does, or the same opportunities for violence due to it's very low population density, and that's just off the top of my head.  Just thought it was interesting that from the viewpoint of a country that DOES regulate it's gun use, and ALSO has a heiritage of gun use, that the two are not mutually exclusive.  Please feel free to drown me out in a flood of rheoteric now).<br>
